<p>A <b>blog</b> (a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clipping_(morp=
hology)" title=3D"Clipping (morphology)">truncation</a> of "<b>weblog</b>")=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> is an informational website consistin=
g of discrete, often informal diary-style text entries also known as <b>pos=
ts</b>. Posts are typically displayed in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Reverse_chronology" title=3D"Reverse chronology">reverse chronologic=
al order</a> so that the most recent post appears first, at the top of the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_page" title=3D"Web page">web p=
age</a>. In the 2000s, blogs were often the work of a single individual, oc=
casionally of a small group, and often covered a single subject or topic. I=
n the 2010s, multi-author blogs (MABs) emerged, featuring the writing of mu=
ltiple authors and sometimes professionally edited. MABs from newspapers, o=
ther <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/News_media" title=3D"News med=
ia">media outlets</a>, universities, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Think_tank" title=3D"Think tank">think tanks</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Advocacy_group" title=3D"Advocacy group">advocacy groups=
</a>, and similar institutions account for an increasing quantity of blog <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_traffic" title=3D"Web traffic">=
traffic</a>. The rise of Twitter and other "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Microblogging" title=3D"Microblogging">microblogging</a>" systems=
 helps integrate MABs and single-author blogs into the news media. <i>Blog<=
/i> can also be used as a verb, meaning <i>to maintain or add content to a =
blog</i>.
</p><p>The emergence and growth of blogs in the late 1990s coincided with t=
he advent of web publishing tools that facilitated the posting of content b=
y non-technical users who did not have much experience with <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML" title=3D"HTML">HTML</a> or <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_programming" title=3D"Computer programmin=
g">computer programming</a>. Previously, knowledge of such technologies as =
HTML and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File_Transfer_Protocol" t=
itle=3D"File Transfer Protocol">File Transfer Protocol</a> had been require=
d to publish content on the Web, and early Web users therefore tended to be=
 hackers and computer enthusiasts. As of the 2010s, the majority are intera=
ctive <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_2.0" title=3D"Web 2.0">W=
eb 2.0</a> websites, allowing visitors to leave online comments, and it is =
this interactivity that distinguishes them from other static websites.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Blog#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In that sense, blogging can be seen as a f=
orm of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_networking_service" =
title=3D"Social networking service">social networking service</a>. Indeed, =
bloggers not only produce content to post on their blogs but also often bui=
ld social relations with their readers and other bloggers.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cit=
e_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> Blog owners or authors often <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Internet_forum#Moderators" title=3D"Internet forum">moderat=
e</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wordfilter" title=3D"Wor=
dfilter">filter</a> online comments to remove <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Hate_speech" title=3D"Hate speech">hate speech</a> or other off=
ensive content. There are also high-readership blogs which do not allow com=
ments.
</p><p>Many blogs provide commentary on a particular subject or topic, rang=
ing from philosophy, religion, and arts to science, politics, and sports. O=
thers function as more personal <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On=
line_diary" title=3D"Online diary">online diaries</a> or <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Online_advertising" title=3D"Online advertising">onl=
ine brand advertising</a> of a particular individual or company. A typical =
blog combines text, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_image"=
 title=3D"Digital image">digital images</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Hyperlink" title=3D"Hyperlink">links</a> to other blogs, web=
 pages, and other media related to its topic. Most blogs are primarily text=
ual, although some focus on art (<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Art_blog" title=3D"Art blog">art blogs</a></i>), photographs (<i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Photoblog" title=3D"Photoblog">photoblogs=
</a></i>), videos (<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_blog" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Video blog">video blogs</a></i> or <i>vlogs<=
/i>), music (<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MP3_blog" title=3D=
"MP3 blog">MP3 blogs</a></i>), and audio (<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Podcast" title=3D"Podcast">podcasts</a></i>). In education, blog=
s can be used as instructional resources; these are referred to as <i><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edublog" title=3D"Edublog">edublogs</a>=
</i>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microblogging" title=3D"Micr=
oblogging">Microblogging</a> is another type of blogging, featuring very sh=
ort posts.
</p><p><i>Blog</i> and <i>blogging</i> are now loosely used for content cre=
ation and sharing on social media, especially when the content is long-form=
 and one creates and shares content on a regular basis, so one could be mai=
ntaining a blog on Facebook or blogging on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Instagram" title=3D"Instagram">Instagram</a>. A 2022 estimate sugg=
ested that there were over 600 million public blogs out of more than 1.9&nb=
sp;billion websites.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_blogging=
" title=3D"History of blogging">History of blogging</a> and <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Online_diary" title=3D"Online diary">online diary=
</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Eastcampusfire_glog_crop.png" =
class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wiki=
pedia/commons/thumb/7/73/Eastcampusfire_glog_crop.png/250px-Eastcampusfire_=
glog_crop.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"238" class=3D"mw-=
file-element" data-file-width=3D"745" data-file-height=3D"708"></a><figcapt=
ion>An early example of a "diary" style blog consisting of text and images =
transmitted wirelessly in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real-tim=
e_computing" title=3D"Real-time computing">real-time</a> from a <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wearable_computer" title=3D"Wearable computer=
">wearable computer</a> with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Head-=
up_display" title=3D"Head-up display">head-up display</a>, February 22, 199=
5</figcaption></figure>
<p>The term "weblog" was coined by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Jorn_Barger" title=3D"Jorn Barger">Jorn Barger</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-=
5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> on December 17, 1997. The short form "blog" was coined by <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPeter_Merholz&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" class=3D"new" title=3D"Peter Merholz (page does =
not exist)">Peter Merholz</a>, who jokingly broke the word <i>weblog</i> in=
to the phrase <i>we blog</i> in the sidebar of his blog Peterme.com in May =
1999.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-7"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Shortly thereafter, <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evan_Williams_(Internet_entrepreneur)" title=3D=
"Evan Williams (Internet entrepreneur)">Evan Williams</a> at <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyra_Labs" title=3D"Pyra Labs">Pyra Labs</a> use=
d "blog" as both a noun and verb and devised the term "blogger" in connecti=
on with Pyra Labs' <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blogger_(servic=
e)" title=3D"Blogger (service)">Blogger</a> product, leading to the popular=
ization of the terms.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Origins">Origins</h3></div>
<p>Before blogging became popular, digital communities took many forms, inc=
luding <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Usenet" title=3D"Usenet">Us=
enet</a>, commercial online services such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/GEnie" title=3D"GEnie">GEnie</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Byte_Information_Exchange" title=3D"Byte Information Exchange">B=
yte Information Exchange</a> (BIX) and the early <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/CompuServe" title=3D"CompuServe">CompuServe</a>, <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronic_mailing_list" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Electronic mailing list">e-mail lists</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_no=
te-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bulletin_bo=
ard_system" title=3D"Bulletin board system">bulletin board systems</a> (BBS=
). In the 1990s, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_forum" t=
itle=3D"Internet forum">Internet forum</a> software created running convers=
ations with "threads". Threads are topical connections between messages on =
a virtual "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bulletin_board" title=
=3D"Bulletin board">corkboard</a>".<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" s=
tyle=3D"margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify" title=3D"Wikipedia:Please clari=
fy"><span title=3D"Too vague (May 2023)">further explanation needed</span><=
/a></i>]</sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tim_Berners-Lee" title=3D"T=
im Berners-Lee">Tim Berners-Lee</a> created what is considered by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Encyclop%C3%A6dia_Britannica" title=3D"En=
cyclop=C3=A6dia Britannica">Encyclopedia Britannica</a> to be "the first 'b=
log<span style=3D"padding-right:.15em;">'</span>" in 1992 to discuss the pr=
ogress made on creating the World Wide Web and software used for it.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Blog#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>From June 14, 1993, Mosaic Communications Corporation maintained the=
ir "What's New"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> list of new website=
s, updated daily and archived monthly. The page was accessible by a special=
 "What's New" button in the Mosaic web browser.
</p><p>In November 1993 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?tit=
le=3DRanjit_Bhatnagar&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" class=3D"new" titl=
e=3D"Ranjit Bhatnagar (page does not exist)">Ranjit Bhatnagar</a> started w=
riting about interesting sites, pages and discussion groups he found on the=
 internet, as well as some personal information, on his website Moonmilk, a=
rranging them chronologically in a special section called Ranjit's HTTP Pla=
yground.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Other early pioneers of bl=
ogging, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Justin_Hall" title=
=3D"Justin Hall">Justin Hall</a>, credit him with being an inspiration.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Blog#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The earliest instance of a commercial blog was on the first <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Business_to_consumer" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Business to consumer">business to consumer</a> Web site created=
 in 1995 by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ty_Inc" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Ty Inc">Ty, Inc.</a>, which featured a blog in a section c=
alled "Online Diary". The entries were maintained by featured <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beanie_Babies" title=3D"Beanie Babies">Beanie B=
abies</a> that were voted for monthly by Web site visitors.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-BeanieBabies_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-BeanieBabies-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The modern blog evolved from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Online_diary" title=3D"Online diary">online diary</a> where people wo=
uld keep a running account of the events in their personal lives. Most such=
 writers called themselves diarists, journalists, or journalers. <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Justin_Hall" title=3D"Justin Hall">Justin Ha=
ll</a>, who began personal blogging in 1994 while a student at <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Swarthmore_College" title=3D"Swarthmore Colleg=
e">Swarthmore College</a>, is generally recognized as one of the earlier bl=
oggers,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> as is <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jerry_Pournelle" title=3D"Jerry Pournelle">Jerry Pourne=
lle</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Dave_Winer" title=3D"Dave Winer">Dave Winer</a>'s Scripting =
News is also credited with being one of the older and longer running weblog=
s.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-19"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> The Australian Netguide magazine maintained the Daily Net News<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Blog#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> on their web site from 1996. Daily Net=
 News ran links and daily reviews of new websites, mostly in Australia.
</p><p>Another early blog was Wearable Wireless Webcam, an online shared di=
ary of a person's personal life combining text, digital video, and digital =
pictures transmitted live from a wearable computer and <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/EyeTap" title=3D"EyeTap">EyeTap</a> device to a web si=
te in 1994. This practice of semi-automated blogging with live video togeth=
er with text was referred to as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/So=
usveillance" title=3D"Sousveillance">sousveillance</a>, and such journals w=
ere also used as evidence in legal matters. Some early bloggers, such as Th=
e Misanthropic Bitch, who began in 1997, referred to their online presence =
as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zine" title=3D"Zine">zine</a>=
, before the term blog entered common usage.
</p><p>The first research paper about blogging was <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTorill_Mortensen&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;redl=
ink=3D1" class=3D"new" title=3D"Torill Mortensen (page does not exist)">Tor=
ill Mortensen</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jill_Walker_=
Rettberg" title=3D"Jill Walker Rettberg">Jill Walker Rettberg</a>'s paper "=
Blogging Thoughts",<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which analysed =
how blogs were being used to foster research communities and the exchange o=
f ideas and scholarship, and how this new means of networking overturns tra=
ditional power structures.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Technology">Technology</h3>=
</div>
<p>Early blogs were simply manually updated components of common Websites. =
In 1995, the "Online Diary" on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Ty,_Inc." class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ty, Inc.">Ty, Inc.</a> Web site w=
as produced and updated manually before any blogging programs were availabl=
e. Posts were made to appear in reverse chronological order by manually upd=
ating text-based <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML" title=3D"HT=
ML">HTML</a> code using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FTP" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"FTP">FTP</a> software in real time several times =
a day. To users, this offered the appearance of a live diary that contained=
 multiple new entries per day. At the beginning of each new day, new diary =
entries were manually coded into a new HTML file, and at the start of each =
month, diary entries were archived into their own folder, which contained a=
 separate HTML page for every day of the month. Then, menus that contained =
links to the most recent diary entry were updated manually throughout the s=
ite. This text-based method of organizing thousands of files served as a sp=
ringboard to define future blogging styles that were captured by blogging s=
oftware developed years later.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-BeanieBabies_15-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-Bean=
ieBabies-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The evolution of electronic and software tools to facilitate the pro=
duction and maintenance of Web articles posted in reverse chronological ord=
er made the publishing process feasible for a much larger and less technica=
lly inclined population. Ultimately, this resulted in the distinct class of=
 online publishing that produces blogs we recognize today. For instance, th=
e use of some sort of browser-based software is now a typical aspect of "bl=
ogging". Blogs can be hosted by dedicated <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Blog_hosting_service" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Blog hosting s=
ervice">blog hosting services</a>, on regular <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Web_hosting_service" title=3D"Web hosting service">web hosting =
services</a>, or run using blog software.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Rise_in_popularity">Rise in=
 popularity</h3></div>
<p>After a slow start, blogging rapidly gained in popularity. Blog usage sp=
read during 1999 and the years following, being further popularized by the =
near-simultaneous arrival of the first hosted blog tools:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bruce_Ableson" title=3D"Br=
uce Ableson">Bruce Ableson</a> launched <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Open_Diary" title=3D"Open Diary">Open Diary</a> in October 1998, whic=
h soon grew to thousands of online diaries. Open Diary innovated the reader=
 comment, becoming the first blog community where readers could add comment=
s to other writers' blog entries.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brad_Fitzpatrick" title=3D"Bra=
d Fitzpatrick">Brad Fitzpatrick</a> started <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/LiveJournal" title=3D"LiveJournal">LiveJournal</a> in March 1999.=
</li>
<li>Andrew Smales created Pitas.com in July 1999 as an easier alternative t=
o maintaining a "news page" on a Web site, followed by DiaryLand in Septemb=
er 1999, focusing more on a personal diary community.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_no=
te-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blogger_(service)" title=3D"Bl=
ogger (service)">Blogger</a> (blogspot.com) was launched in 1999<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B=
log#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Political_impact">Political=
 impact</h3></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Talkingpointsmemo2.png" class=3D"mw-file-desc=
ription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/4/4f/Talking=
pointsmemo2.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"242" height=3D"410" class=3D"m=
w-file-element" data-file-width=3D"242" data-file-height=3D"410"></a><figca=
ption>On December 6, 2002, Josh Marshall's talkingpointsmemo.com blog calle=
d attention to U.S. Senator <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trent_=
Lott" title=3D"Trent Lott">Lott's</a> comments regarding Senator Thurmond. =
Senator Lott was eventually to resign his Senate leadership position over t=
he matter.</figcaption></figure>
<p>An early milestone in the rise in importance of blogs came in 2002, when=
 many bloggers focused on comments by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/United_States_Senate_Majority_Leader" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Un=
ited States Senate Majority Leader">U.S. Senate Majority Leader</a> <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trent_Lott" title=3D"Trent Lott">Trent Lo=
tt</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-massing_essay_24-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-massing_essay-24"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> Senator Lott, at a party honoring <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/United_States_Senate" title=3D"United States Senate">U.S. Senator</a> <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strom_Thurmond" title=3D"Strom Thur=
mond">Strom Thurmond</a>, praised Senator Thurmond by suggesting that the U=
nited States would have been better off had Thurmond been elected president=
. Lott's critics saw these comments as tacit approval of <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Racial_segregation" title=3D"Racial segregation">rac=
ial segregation</a>, a policy advocated by Thurmond's <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/1948_United_States_presidential_election" title=3D"1948=
 United States presidential election">1948 presidential campaign</a>. This =
view was reinforced by documents and recorded interviews dug up by bloggers=
. (See <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josh_Marshall" title=3D"Jos=
h Marshall">Josh Marshall</a>'s <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Talking_Points_Memo" title=3D"Talking Points Memo">Talking Points Memo</a>=
</i>.) Though Lott's comments were made at a public event attended by the m=
edia, no major media organizations reported on his controversial comments u=
ntil after blogs broke the story. Blogging helped to create a political cri=
sis that forced Lott to step down as majority leader.
</p><p>Similarly, blogs were among the driving forces behind the "<a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rathergate" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Rathergate">Rathergate</a>" scandal. Television journalist <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dan_Rather" title=3D"Dan Rather">Dan Rather</a=
> presented documents on the CBS show <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/60_Minutes" title=3D"60 Minutes">60 Minutes</a></i> that conflicted =
with accepted accounts of President Bush's military service record. Blogger=
s declared the documents to be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/For=
gery" title=3D"Forgery">forgeries</a> and presented evidence and arguments =
in support of that view. Consequently, CBS apologized for what it said were=
 inadequate reporting techniques (see: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Little_Green_Footballs" title=3D"Little Green Footballs">Little Green =
Footballs</a>). The impact of these stories gave greater credibility to blo=
gs as a medium of news dissemination.
</p><p>In Russia, some political bloggers have started to challenge the dom=
inance of official, overwhelmingly pro-government media. Bloggers such as <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rustem_Adagamov" title=3D"Rustem Ad=
agamov">Rustem Adagamov</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al=
exei_Navalny" title=3D"Alexei Navalny">Alexei Navalny</a> have many followe=
rs, and the latter's nickname for the ruling <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/United_Russia" title=3D"United Russia">United Russia</a> party a=
s the "party of crooks and thieves" has been adopted by anti-regime protest=
ers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This led to <i><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Wall_Street_Journal" title=3D"The Wall Street=
 Journal">The Wall Street Journal</a></i> calling Navalny "the man <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vladimir_Putin" title=3D"Vladimir Putin">=
Vladimir Putin</a> fears most" in March 2012.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-26">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>  (Navalny died in prison in 2024.)
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Mainstream_popularity">Main=
stream popularity</h3></div>
<p>By 2004, the role of blogs became increasingly mainstream, as <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Political_consultant" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Political consultant">political consultants</a>, news services, an=
d candidates began using them as tools for outreach and opinion forming. Bl=
ogging was established by politicians and political candidates to express o=
pinions on war and other issues and cemented blogs' role as a news source. =
(See <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Howard_Dean" title=3D"Howard =
Dean">Howard Dean</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wesley_C=
lark" title=3D"Wesley Clark">Wesley Clark</a>.) Even politicians not active=
ly campaigning, such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Labour=
_Party_(UK)" title=3D"Labour Party (UK)">UK's Labour Party's</a> <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Member_of_Parliament_(United_Kingdom)" title=
=3D"Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)">Member of Parliament</a> (MP) <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Watson_(Labour_politician)" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tom Watson (Labour politician)">Tom Watson</a>, =
began to blog to bond with constituents. In January 2005, <i><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fortune_(magazine)" title=3D"Fortune (magazine)"=
>Fortune</a></i> magazine listed eight bloggers whom business people "could=
 not ignore": <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engadget" title=3D"E=
ngadget">Peter Rojas</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xeni_Jar=
din" title=3D"Xeni Jardin">Xeni Jardin</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Benjamin_Trott" title=3D"Benjamin Trott">Ben Trott</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mena_Trott" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Mena Trott">Mena Trott</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jo=
nathan_I._Schwartz" title=3D"Jonathan I. Schwartz">Jonathan Schwartz</a>, J=
ason Goldman, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Scoble" title=
=3D"Robert Scoble">Robert Scoble</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Jason_Calacanis" title=3D"Jason Calacanis">Jason Calacanis</a>.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Blog#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Israel was among the first national governments to set up an officia=
l blog.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Ynet_28-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-Ynet-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Under <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Saranga" title=3D"David Saranga">Da=
vid Saranga</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Israeli_Minis=
try_of_Foreign_Affairs" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Israeli Ministry of =
Foreign Affairs">Israeli Ministry of Foreign Affairs</a> became active in a=
dopting <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_2.0" title=3D"Web 2.0"=
>Web 2.0</a> initiatives, including an official <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Video_blog" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Video blog">video =
blog</a> and a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Political_blog" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Political blog">political blog</a>.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-Ynet_28-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Blog#cite_note-Ynet-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The Foreign Ministry also held a <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microblogging" title=3D"Microbloggi=
ng">microblogging</a> press conference via Twitter about its <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2008%E2%80%932009_Israel%E2%80%93Gaza_conflict" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"2008=E2=80=932009 Israel=E2=80=93Gaza confli=
ct">war with Hamas</a>, with Saranga answering questions from the public in=
 common text-messaging abbreviations during a live worldwide press conferen=
ce.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-JP_29-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-JP-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The questions and answe=
rs were later posted on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IsraelPoli=
tik" title=3D"IsraelPolitik">IsraelPolitik</a>, the country's official poli=
tical blog.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NYTs_30-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-NYTs-30"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The impact of blogging on the mainstream media has also been acknowl=
edged by governments. In 2009, the presence of the American journalism indu=
stry had declined to the point that several newspaper corporations were fil=
ing for bankruptcy, resulting in less direct competition between newspapers=
 within the same circulation area. Discussion emerged as to whether the new=
spaper industry would benefit from a stimulus package by the federal govern=
ment. U.S. President <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barack_Obama"=
 title=3D"Barack Obama">Barack Obama</a> acknowledged the emerging influenc=
e of blogging upon society by saying, "if the direction of the news is all =
blogosphere, all opinions, with no serious fact-checking, no serious attemp=
ts to put stories in context, then what you will end up getting is people s=
houting at each other across the void, but not a lot of mutual understandin=
g".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Between 2009 and 2012, an <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orwell_Prize" title=3D"Orwell Prize">Or=
well Prize</a> for blogging was awarded.
</p><p>In the late 2000s, blogs were often used on business websites and fo=
r <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grassroots" title=3D"Grassroots"=
>grassroots</a> political activism.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_32-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-:0-32"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Types">Types</h2></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:BlogActive.com_Screenshot_200=
4.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.o=
rg/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cc/BlogActive.com_Screenshot_2004.jpg/250px-Bl=
ogActive.com_Screenshot_2004.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"230" height=
=3D"295" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"677" data-file-height=
=3D"867"></a><figcaption>A screenshot from the BlogActive website</figcapti=
on></figure>
<p>There are many different types of blogs, differing not only in the type =
of content, but also in the way that content is delivered or written.
</p>
<dl><dt>Personal blogs</dt>
<dd>The personal blog is an ongoing online diary or commentary written by a=
n individual, rather than a corporation or organization. While the vast maj=
ority of personal blogs attract very few readers, other than the blogger's =
immediate family and friends, a small number of personal blogs have become =
popular, to the point that they have attracted lucrative advertising sponso=
rship. A few personal bloggers have gained significant recognition beyond t=
heir immediate circles.</dd></dl>
<dl><dt>Collaborative blogs or group blogs</dt>
<dd>A type of weblog in which posts are written and published by more than =
one author. The majority of high-profile collaborative blogs are organised =
according to a single uniting theme, such as politics, technology or advoca=
cy. In recent years, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blogosphe=
re" title=3D"Blogosphere">blogosphere</a> has seen the emergence and growin=
g popularity of more collaborative efforts, often set up by already establi=
shed bloggers wishing to pool time and resources, both to reduce the pressu=
re of maintaining a popular website and to attract a larger readership.</dd=
></dl>
<dl><dt><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microblogging" title=3D"Mi=
croblogging">Microblogging</a></dt>
<dd>Microblogging is the practice of posting small pieces of digital conten=
t=E2=80=94which could be text, pictures, links, short videos, or other medi=
a=E2=80=94on the internet. Microblogging offers a portable communication mo=
de that feels organic and spontaneous to many users. It has captured the pu=
blic imagination, in part because the short posts are easy to read on the g=
o or when waiting. Friends use it to keep in touch, business associates use=
 it to coordinate meetings or share useful resources, and celebrities and p=
oliticians (or their publicists) microblog about concert dates, lectures, b=
ook releases, or tour schedules. A wide and growing range of add-on tools e=
nables sophisticated updates and interaction with other applications. The r=
esulting profusion of functionality is helping to define new possibilities =
for this type of communication.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Exa=
mples of these include Twitter, Facebook, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Tumblr" title=3D"Tumblr">Tumblr</a> and, by far the largest, <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sina_Weibo" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Sina Weibo">Weibo</a>.</dd></dl>
<dl><dt>Corporate and organizational blogs</dt>
<dd>A blog can be private, as in most cases, or it can be for business or <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Not-for-profit_organization" title=
=3D"Not-for-profit organization">not-for-profit organization</a> or governm=
ent purposes. Blogs used internally and only available to employees via an =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intranet" title=3D"Intranet">Intra=
net</a> are called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corporate_blog"=
 title=3D"Corporate blog">corporate blogs</a>. Companies use internal corpo=
rate blogs to enhance the communication, culture and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Employee_engagement" title=3D"Employee engagement">emplo=
yee engagement</a> in a corporation. Internal corporate blogs can be used t=
o communicate news about company policies or procedures, build employee <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Esprit_de_corps" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Esprit de corps">esprit de corps</a> and improve <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morale" title=3D"Morale">morale</a>. Companies an=
d other organizations also use external, publicly accessible blogs for mark=
eting, branding, or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public_relatio=
ns" title=3D"Public relations">public relations</a> purposes. Some organiza=
tions have a blog authored by their executive; in practice, many of these e=
xecutive blog posts are penned by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Ghostwriter" title=3D"Ghostwriter">ghostwriter</a> who makes posts in the=
 style of the credited author. Similar blogs for clubs and societies are ca=
lled club blogs, group blogs, or by similar names; typical use is to inform=
 members and other interested parties of club and member activities.</dd></=
dl>
<dl><dt>Aggregated blogs</dt>
<dd>Individuals or organization may aggregate selected feeds on a specific =
topic, product or service and provide a combined view for its readers. This=
 allows readers to concentrate on reading instead of searching for quality =
on-topic content and managing subscriptions. Many such aggregations called =
planets from name of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Planet_(softw=
are)" title=3D"Planet (software)">Planet (software)</a> that perform such a=
ggregation, hosting sites usually have <i>planet.</i> <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subdomain" title=3D"Subdomain">subdomain</a> in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Domain_name" title=3D"Domain name">domain=
 name</a> (like <a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external free" href=3D"http://=
planet.gnome.org/">http://planet.gnome.org/</a>).</dd></dl>
<dl><dt>By genre</dt>
<dd>Some blogs focus on a particular subject, such as <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Political_blog" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Politica=
l blog">political blogs</a>, journalism blogs, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Health_blog" title=3D"Health blog">health blogs</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Travel_literature" title=3D"Travel litera=
ture">travel blogs</a> (also known as <i>travelogs</i>), gardening blogs, h=
ouse blogs, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_Blog" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Book Blog">Book Blogs</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-34">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Fashion_blog" title=3D"Fashion blog">fashion blogs</a>, b=
eauty blogs, lifestyle blogs, party blogs, wedding blogs, photography blogs=
, project blogs, psychology blogs, sociology blogs, <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Edublog" title=3D"Edublog">education blogs</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Niche_blogging" title=3D"Niche blogging">=
niche blogs</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_music_b=
log" title=3D"Classical music blog">classical music blogs</a>, quizzing blo=
gs, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legal_blogs" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Legal blogs">legal blogs</a> (often referred to as a blawgs),=
 or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dream_diary" title=3D"Dream di=
ary">dreamlogs</a>. How-to/<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tutoria=
l" title=3D"Tutorial">Tutorial</a> blogs are becoming increasing popular.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Blog#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Two common types of genre blogs are =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Art_blog" title=3D"Art blog">art b=
logs</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MP3_blog" title=3D"MP=
3 blog">music blogs</a>. A blog featuring discussions, especially about <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homemaking" title=3D"Homemaking">home=
</a> and family is not uncommonly called a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/List_of_family-and-homemaking_blogs" title=3D"List of family-and-h=
omemaking blogs">mom blog</a>. While not a legitimate type of blog, one use=
d for the sole purpose of spamming is known as a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Spam_blog" title=3D"Spam blog">splog</a>.</dd></dl>
<dl><dt>By media type</dt>
<dd>A blog comprising videos is called a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Video_blog" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Video blog">vlog</a>, one=
 comprising links is called a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Link=
log" title=3D"Linklog">linklog</a>, a site containing a portfolio of sketch=
es is called a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sketchblog" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sketchblog">sketchblog</a> or one comprising phot=
os is called a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Photoblog" title=3D=
"Photoblog">photoblog</a>. Blogs with shorter posts and mixed media types a=
re called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tumblelog" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Tumblelog">tumblelogs</a>. Blogs that are written on type=
writers and then scanned are called typecast or typecast blogs. A rare type=
 of blog hosted on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gopher_Prot=
ocol" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gopher Protocol">Gopher Protocol</a> i=
s known as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phlog" title=3D"Phlog=
">phlog</a>.</dd></dl>
<dl><dt>By device</dt>
<dd>A blog can also be defined by which type of device is used to compose i=
t. A blog written by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mobile_devi=
ce" title=3D"Mobile device">mobile device</a> like a mobile phone or <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Personal_digital_assistant" title=3D"Per=
sonal digital assistant">PDA</a> could be called a <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Moblog" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Moblog">moblog</a>.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> One early blog was Wearable Wirele=
ss Webcam, an online shared diary of a person's personal life combining tex=
t, video, and pictures transmitted live from a wearable computer and <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/EyeTap" title=3D"EyeTap">EyeTap</a> devi=
ce to a web site. This practice of semi-automated blogging with live video =
together with text was referred to as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Sousveillance" title=3D"Sousveillance">sousveillance</a>. Such journals=
 have been used as evidence in legal matters.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-T=
emplate Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citati=
on needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. =
(August 2008)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></dd></dl>
<dl><dt><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reverse_blog" title=3D"Rev=
erse blog">Reverse blog</a></dt>
<dd>A reverse blog is composed by its users rather than a single blogger. T=
his system has the characteristics of a blog and the writing of several aut=
hors. These can be written by several contributing authors on a topic or op=
ened up for anyone to write. There is typically some limit to the number of=
 entries to keep it from operating like a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Web_forum" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Web forum">web forum</a>.=
<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:n=
owrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_nee=
ded" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs re=
ferences to reliable sources. (May 2014)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</=
sup></dd></dl>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Community_and_cataloging">C=
ommunity and cataloging</h2></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Blogosphere_map.jpg" class=3D=
"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/co=
mmons/thumb/8/80/Blogosphere_map.jpg/250px-Blogosphere_map.jpg" decoding=3D=
"async" width=3D"230" height=3D"221" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-wi=
dth=3D"300" data-file-height=3D"288"></a><figcaption>An artist's depiction =
of the interconnections between blogs and blog authors in the "<a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blogosphere" title=3D"Blogosphere">blogosphere=
</a>" in 2007</figcaption></figure>
<dl><dt><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blogosphere" title=3D"Blog=
osphere">Blogosphere</a></dt>
<dd>The collective community of all blogs and blog authors, particularly no=
table and widely read blogs, is known as the <i>blogosphere</i>. Since all =
blogs are on the internet by definition, they may be seen as interconnected=
 and socially networked, through blogrolls, comments, <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linkback" title=3D"Linkback">linkbacks</a> (refbacks, t=
rackbacks or pingbacks), and backlinks. Discussions "in the blogosphere" we=
re occasionally used by the media as a gauge of public opinion on various i=
ssues. Because new, untapped communities of bloggers and their readers can =
emerge in the space of a few years, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Internet_marketing" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Internet marketing">In=
ternet marketers</a> pay close attention to "trends in the blogosphere".<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Blog#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></dd></dl>
<dl><dt><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_search_engines#Blo=
g" title=3D"List of search engines">Blog search engines</a></dt>
<dd>Several blog search engines have been used to search blog contents, suc=
h as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bloglines" title=3D"Bloglines=
">Bloglines</a> (defunct), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BlogSco=
pe" title=3D"BlogScope">BlogScope</a> (defunct), and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Technorati" title=3D"Technorati">Technorati</a> (defunct=
).</dd></dl>
<dl><dt>Blogging communities and directories</dt>
<dd>Several <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Online_communities" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Online communities">online communities</a> exi=
st that connect people to blogs and bloggers to other bloggers. Interest-sp=
ecific blogging platforms are also available. For instance, Blogster has a =
sizable community of political bloggers among its members. <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Global_Voices_Online" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Global Voices Online">Global Voices</a> aggregates international blogge=
rs, "with emphasis on voices that are not ordinarily heard in international=
 mainstream media."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></dd></dl>
<dl><dt>Blogging and advertising</dt>
<dd>It is common for blogs to feature <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Banner_advertisement" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Banner advertiseme=
nt">banner advertisements</a> or promotional content, either to financially=
 benefit the blogger, support website hosting costs, or to promote the blog=
ger's favourite causes or products. The popularity of blogs has also given =
rise to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fake_blog" title=3D"Fake b=
log">"fake blogs"</a> in which a company will create a fictional blog as a =
marketing tool to promote a product.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-40" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-40"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
></dd></dl>
<p>As the popularity of blogging continued to rise (as of 2006), the commer=
cialisation of blogging is rapidly increasing. Many corporations and compan=
ies collaborate with bloggers to increase advertising and engage online com=
munities with their products. In the book <i>Fans, Bloggers, and Gamers</i>=
, Henry Jenkins stated that "Bloggers take knowledge into their own hands, =
enabling successful navigation within and between these emerging knowledge =
cultures. One can see such behaviour as co-optation into commodity culture =
insofar as it sometimes collaborates with corporate interests, but one can =
also see it as increasing the diversity of media culture, providing opportu=
nities for greater inclusiveness, and making more responsive to consumers."=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Early_popularity">Early pop=
ularity</h2></div>
<ul><li><b>Before 2006:</b> The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bl=
ogdex" title=3D"Blogdex">blogdex</a> project was launched by researchers in=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MIT_Media_Lab" title=3D"MIT M=
edia Lab">MIT Media Lab</a> to crawl the Web and gather data from thousands=
 of blogs to investigate their social properties. Information was gathered =
by the tool for over four years, during which it autonomously tracked the m=
ost contagious information spreading in the blog community, ranking it by r=
ecency and popularity. It can, therefore,<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Templ=
ate" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Wikipedia:No_original_research" title=3D"Wikipedia:No original researc=
h"><span title=3D"The material near this tag possibly contains original res=
earch. (September 2012)">original research?</span></a></i>]</sup> be consid=
ered the first instantiation of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Memetracker" title=3D"Memetracker">memetracker</a>. The project was replace=
d by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tailrank.com" title=3D"Tailra=
nk.com">tailrank.com</a>, which in turn has been replaced by spinn3r.com.</=
li>
<li><b>2006:</b> Blogs are given rankings by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Alexa_Internet" title=3D"Alexa Internet">Alexa Internet</a> (web=
 hits of Alexa Toolbar users), and formerly by blog search engine <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Technorati" title=3D"Technorati">Technora=
ti</a> based on the number of incoming links (Technorati stopped doing this=
 in 2014). In August 2006, Technorati found that the most linked-to blog on=
 the internet was that of Chinese actress <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Xu_Jinglei" title=3D"Xu Jinglei">Xu Jinglei</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-Fickling_42-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Blog#cite_note-Fickling-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Chinese media <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xinhua" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Xinhua">Xinhua=
</a> reported that this blog received more than 50 million page views, clai=
ming it to be the most popular blog in the world at the time.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-43" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog=
#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template noprint noe=
xcerpt Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:NOTRS" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Wikip=
edia:NOTRS"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to better sources. (=
October 2021)">better&nbsp;source&nbsp;needed</span></a></i>]</sup> Technor=
ati rated <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boing_Boing" title=3D"Bo=
ing Boing">Boing Boing</a> to be the most-read group-written blog.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Fickling_42-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-Fickling-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><b>2008:</b> As of 2008<sup class=3D"plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-=
tag update" style=3D"display:none;"><a class=3D"external text" href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBlog&amp;action=3Dedit">[update]</=
a></sup>, blogging had "become such a mania that a new blog was created eve=
ry second of every minute of every hour of every day."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4=
4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_n=
ote-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> Researchers have actively analyzed the dynamics of how =
blogs become popular. There are essentially two measures of this: popularit=
y through citations, as well as popularity through affiliation (i.e., blogr=
oll). The basic conclusion from studies of the structure of blogs is that w=
hile it takes time for a blog to become popular through blogrolls, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Permalink" title=3D"Permalink">permalinks=
</a> can boost popularity more quickly and are perhaps more indicative of p=
opularity and authority than blogrolls since they denote that people are re=
ading the blog's content and deem it valuable or noteworthy in specific cas=
es.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-45" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Software">Software</h2></di=
v>
<p>Blogs are a form of websites and can therefore be created via the same s=
oftware as can be used for creating websites. Many people use managed platf=
orms such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medium_(website)" tit=
le=3D"Medium (website)">Medium (website)</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Substack" title=3D"Substack">Substack</a>. These platforms ha=
ve built-in support for many features such as previewing posts, <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paywalls" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Payw=
alls">paywalls</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newsletter=
s" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Newsletters">newsletters</a>. Other peopl=
e self-host their website via <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Open=
_source" title=3D"Open source">open source</a> software such as <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WordPress" title=3D"WordPress">WordPress</a> =
or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Static_site_generator" title=3D=
"Static site generator">static site generators</a> such as <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugo_(software)" title=3D"Hugo (software)">Hugo (s=
oftware)</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jekyll_(software)"=
 title=3D"Jekyll (software)">Jekyll (software)</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Blurring_with_the_mass_medi=
a">Blurring with the mass media</h2></div>
<p>Many bloggers, particularly those engaged in <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Citizen_journalism" title=3D"Citizen journalism">participator=
y journalism</a>, are amateur journalists, and thus they differentiate them=
selves from the professional reporters and editors who work in <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mainstream_media" title=3D"Mainstream media">m=
ainstream media</a> organizations. Other bloggers are media professionals w=
ho are publishing online, rather than via a TV station or newspaper, either=
 as an add-on to a traditional media presence (e.g., hosting a radio show o=
r writing a column in a paper newspaper), or as their sole journalistic out=
put. Some institutions and organizations see blogging as a means of "gettin=
g around the filter" of media "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gat=
ekeeper" title=3D"Gatekeeper">gatekeepers</a>" and pushing their messages d=
irectly to the public. Many mainstream journalists, meanwhile, write their =
own blogs=E2=80=94well over 300, according to CyberJournalist.net's J-blog =
list.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-sp=
ace:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citatio=
n_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim nee=
ds references to reliable sources. (June 2010)">citation needed</span></a><=
/i>]</sup> The first known use of a blog on a news site was in August 1998,=
 when <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jonathan_Dube" title=3D"Jona=
than Dube">Jonathan Dube</a> of <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/The_Charlotte_Observer" title=3D"The Charlotte Observer">The Charlotte Obs=
erver</a></i> published one chronicling <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Hurricane_Bonnie_(1998)" title=3D"Hurricane Bonnie (1998)">Hurricane =
Bonnie</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-46" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Some bloggers have moved over to other media. The following bloggers=
 (and others) have appeared on radio and television: <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Atrios" title=3D"Atrios">Duncan Black</a> (known widely =
by his pseudonym, Atrios), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glenn_R=
eynolds" title=3D"Glenn Reynolds">Glenn Reynolds</a> (<a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Instapundit" title=3D"Instapundit">Instapundit</a>), <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markos_Moulitsas_Z%C3%BAniga" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Markos Moulitsas Z=C3=BAniga">Markos Moulitsas Z=
=C3=BAniga</a> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daily_Kos" title=
=3D"Daily Kos">Daily Kos</a>), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ale=
x_Steffen" title=3D"Alex Steffen">Alex Steffen</a> (<a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Worldchanging" title=3D"Worldchanging">Worldchanging</a>)=
, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ana_Marie_Cox" title=3D"Ana Mari=
e Cox">Ana Marie Cox</a> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wonkette=
" title=3D"Wonkette">Wonkette</a>), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Nate_Silver" title=3D"Nate Silver">Nate Silver</a> (<a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/FiveThirtyEight.com" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fiv=
eThirtyEight.com">FiveThirtyEight.com</a>), and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Ezra_Klein" title=3D"Ezra Klein">Ezra Klein</a> (Ezra Klein b=
log in <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_American_Prospect" t=
itle=3D"The American Prospect">The American Prospect</a>,</i> now in <i><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Washington_Post" title=3D"The Was=
hington Post">The Washington Post</a></i>). In counterpoint, <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugh_Hewitt" title=3D"Hugh Hewitt">Hugh Hewitt</=
a> exemplifies a mass media personality who has moved in the other directio=
n, adding to his reach in "old media" by being an influential blogger. Simi=
larly, it was <i>Emergency Preparedness and Safety Tips On Air and Online</=
i> blog articles that captured <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sur=
geon_General_of_the_United_States" title=3D"Surgeon General of the United S=
tates">Surgeon General of the United States</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Richard_Carmona" title=3D"Richard Carmona">Richard Carmona</a=
>'s attention and earned his kudos for the associated broadcasts by talk sh=
ow host <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WVOX#Notable_Past_Programm=
ing" title=3D"WVOX">Lisa Tolliver</a> and Westchester Emergency Volunteer R=
eserves-<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medical_Reserve_Corps" tit=
le=3D"Medical Reserve Corps">Medical Reserve Corps</a> Director Marianne Pa=
rtridge.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4=
7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-48=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p><p>Blogs have also had an influence on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Minority_language" title=3D"Minority language">minority languages<=
/a>, bringing together scattered speakers and learners; this is particularl=
y so with blogs in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goidelic_langua=
ge" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Goidelic language">Gaelic languages</a>.=
 Minority language publishing (which may lack economic feasibility) can fin=
d its audience through inexpensive blogging. There are examples of bloggers=
 who have published books based on their blogs, e.g., <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salam_Pax" title=3D"Salam Pax">Salam Pax</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellen_Simonetti" title=3D"Ellen Simonetti=
">Ellen Simonetti</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jessica_Cut=
ler" title=3D"Jessica Cutler">Jessica Cutler</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/ScrappleFace" title=3D"ScrappleFace">ScrappleFace</a>. =
Blog-based books have been given the name <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Blook" title=3D"Blook">blook</a>. A prize for the best blog-based b=
ook was initiated in 2005,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lulu_Blooker_Prize" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Lulu Blooker Prize">Lulu Blooker Prize</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-50" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite=
_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> However, success has been elusive offline, with many =
of these books not selling as well as their blogs. The book based on <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Julie_Powell" title=3D"Julie Powell">Jul=
ie Powell</a>'s blog "The Julie/Julia Project" was made into the film <i><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Julie_%26_Julia" title=3D"Julie &amp=
; Julia">Julie &amp; Julia</a></i>, apparently the first to do so.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Consumer-generated_advertis=
ing">Consumer-generated advertising</h2></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consumer-generated_advertising"=
 title=3D"Consumer-generated advertising">Consumer-generated advertising</a=
> is a relatively new and controversial development, and it has created a n=
ew model of marketing communication from businesses to consumers. Among the=
 various forms of advertising on blog, the most controversial are the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sponsored_post" title=3D"Sponsored post=
">sponsored posts</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-51"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> These are =
blog entries or posts and may be in the form of feedback, reviews, opinion,=
 videos, etc. and usually contain a link back to the desired site using a k=
eyword or several keywords. Blogs have led to some <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Disintermediation" title=3D"Disintermediation">disintermed=
iation</a> and a breakdown of the traditional advertising model, where comp=
anies can skip over the advertising agencies (previously the only interface=
 with the customer) and contact the customers directly via social media web=
sites. On the other hand, new companies specialised in blog advertising hav=
e been established to take advantage of this new development as well. Howev=
er, there are many people who look negatively on this new development. Some=
 believe that any form of commercial activity on blogs will destroy the blo=
gosphere's credibility.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-52"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Legal_and_social_consequenc=
es">Legal and social consequences</h2></div>
<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Legal"></span>
Blogging can result in a range of legal liabilities and other <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unforeseen_consequence" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Unforeseen consequence">unforeseen consequences</a>.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-53" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#=
cite_note-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Defamation_or_liability">De=
famation or liability</h3></div>
<p>Several cases have been brought before the national courts against blogg=
ers concerning issues of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slander_a=
nd_libel" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Slander and libel">defamation or l=
iability</a>. U.S. payouts related to blogging totalled $17.4&nbsp;million =
by 2009; in some cases these have been covered by <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Umbrella_insurance" title=3D"Umbrella insurance">umbrella i=
nsurance</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-54" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The courts have retur=
ned with mixed verdicts. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_=
Service_Provider" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Internet Service Provider"=
>Internet Service Providers</a> (ISPs), in general, are immune from liabili=
ty for information that originates with third parties (U.S. <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Communications_Decency_Act" title=3D"Communicatio=
ns Decency Act">Communications Decency Act</a> and the EU Directive 2000/31=
/EC). In <i>Doe v. Cahill</i>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Delaware_Supreme_Court" title=3D"Delaware Supreme Court">Delaware Supreme =
Court</a> held that stringent standards had to be met to unmask the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anonymous_bloggers" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Anonymous bloggers">anonymous bloggers</a> and also took the unus=
ual step of dismissing the libel case itself (as unfounded under American l=
ibel law) rather than referring it back to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Trial_court" title=3D"Trial court">trial court</a> for reconsi=
deration.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-55" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
55<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In a bizarre twist, the C=
ahills were able to obtain the identity of John Doe, who turned out to be t=
he person they suspected: the town's mayor, Councilman Cahill's political r=
ival. The Cahills amended their original complaint, and the mayor settled t=
he case rather than going to trial.
</p><p>In January 2007, two prominent Malaysian political bloggers, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeff_Ooi" title=3D"Jeff Ooi">Jeff Ooi</a>=
 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ahirudin_Attan" title=3D"Ahir=
udin Attan">Ahirudin Attan</a>, were sued by a pro-government newspaper, Th=
e New Straits Times Press (Malaysia) Berhad, Kalimullah bin Masheerul Hassa=
n, Hishamuddin bin Aun and Brenden John <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Malaysian_names#Indian_names" title=3D"Malaysian names">a/l</a> John =
Pereira over alleged defamation. The plaintiff was supported by the Malaysi=
an government.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-56" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-56"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>56<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Following the suit, =
the Malaysian government proposed to "register" all bloggers in Malaysia to=
 better control parties against their interests.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-57" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-57=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> This is the first such legal case against bloggers in the cou=
ntry. In the United States, blogger Aaron Wall was sued by Traffic Power fo=
r <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Defamation" title=3D"Defamation"=
>defamation</a> and publication of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Trade_secrets" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Trade secrets">trade secrets=
</a> in 2005.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-58" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>58<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> According to <i>Wired=
</i> magazine, Traffic Power had been "banned from Google for allegedly rig=
ging search engine results."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-59" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-59"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Wall a=
nd other "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White_hat_(computer_secu=
rity)" title=3D"White hat (computer security)">white hat</a>" <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Search_engine_optimization" title=3D"Search eng=
ine optimization">search engine optimization</a> consultants had exposed Tr=
affic Power in what they claim was an effort to protect the public. The cas=
e was dismissed for lack of personal jurisdiction, and Traffic Power failed=
 to appeal within the allowed time.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-60" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-60"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>60<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 2009, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NDTV" title=3D"NDT=
V">NDTV</a> issued a legal notice to Indian blogger Kunte for a blog post c=
riticizing their coverage of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
umbai_attacks" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mumbai attacks">Mumbai attack=
s</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-hootbarkha_61-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-hootbarkha-61"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>61<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The =
blogger unconditionally withdrew his post, which resulted in several Indian=
 bloggers criticizing NDTV for trying to silence critics.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-62" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cit=
e_note-62"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>62<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Employment">Employment</h3>=
</div>
<p>Employees who blog about elements of their place of employment can begin=
 to affect the reputation of their employer, either in a positive way, if t=
he employee is praising the employer and its workplaces, or in a negative w=
ay, if the blogger is making negative comments about the company or its pra=
ctices.
</p><p>In general, attempts by employee bloggers to protect themselves by m=
aintaining anonymity have proved ineffective.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-63" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-63">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> In 2009, a controversial and landmark decision by <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Eady" title=3D"David Eady">The Hon. Mr Ju=
stice Eady</a> refused to grant an order to protect the anonymity of <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Horton_(blogger)" title=3D"Richa=
rd Horton (blogger)">Richard Horton</a>. Horton was a police officer in the=
 United Kingdom who blogged about his job under the name "NightJack".<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-64" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Blog#cite_note-64"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>64<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delta_Air_Lines" title=3D"D=
elta Air Lines">Delta Air Lines</a> fired <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Flight_attendant" title=3D"Flight attendant">flight attendant</a> <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellen_Simonetti" title=3D"Ellen Sim=
onetti">Ellen Simonetti</a> because she posted photographs of herself in un=
iform on an aeroplane and because of comments posted on her blog "Queen of =
Sky: Diary of a Flight Attendant" which the employer deemed inappropriate.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-65" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-65"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>65<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-66" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-66"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>66<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> This case highlighted the issue of personal blogging and freedom of ex=
pression versus employer rights and responsibilities, and so it received wi=
de media attention. Simonetti took legal action against the airline for "wr=
ongful termination, defamation of character and lost future wages".<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-67" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Blog#cite_note-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The suit was postponed while Delta was in=
 bankruptcy proceedings.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-68" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-68"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>68<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In early 2006, Erik Ringmar, a senior lecturer at the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/London_School_of_Economics" title=3D"London Scho=
ol of Economics">London School of Economics</a>, was ordered by the conveno=
r of his department to "take down and destroy" his blog in which he discuss=
ed the quality of education at the school.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-69" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-69"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>69<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p><p>Mark Jen was terminated in 2005 after 10 days of employment as an as=
sistant product manager at Google for discussing corporate secrets on his p=
ersonal blog, then called 99zeros and hosted on the Google-owned <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blogger.com" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Blogger.com">Blogger</a> service.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-70" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-70"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>70<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 He blogged about unreleased products and company finances a week before th=
e company's earnings announcement. He was fired two days after he complied =
with his employer's request to remove the sensitive material from his blog.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-71" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-71"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>71<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In India, blogger Gaurav Sabnis resigned from <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/IBM" title=3D"IBM">IBM</a> after his posts questioned th=
e claims made by a management school.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-72" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-72"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>72<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jessica_Cutler" title=3D"Jessic=
a Cutler">Jessica Cutler</a>, aka "The Washingtonienne", blogged about her =
sex life while employed as a congressional assistant. After the blog was di=
scovered and she was fired,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-73" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-73"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>73<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> she wro=
te a novel based on her experiences and blog: <i>The Washingtonienne: A Nov=
el</i>. As of 2006<sup class=3D"plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag updat=
e" style=3D"display:none;"><a class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBlog&amp;action=3Dedit">[update]</a></sup>,=
 Cutler is being sued by one of her former lovers in a case that could esta=
blish the extent to which bloggers are obligated to protect the privacy of =
their real life associates.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-74" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-74"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>74<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Catherine Sanderson, a.k.a. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Petite_Anglaise" title=3D"Petite Anglaise">Petite Anglaise</a>, lost her j=
ob in Paris at a British accountancy firm because of blogging.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-75" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blo=
g#cite_note-75"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>75<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> Although given in the blog in a fairly anonymou=
s manner, some of the descriptions of the firm and some of its people were =
less than flattering. Sanderson later won a compensation claim case against=
 the British firm, however.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-76" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-76"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>76<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>On the other hand, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Penelope=
_Trunk" title=3D"Penelope Trunk">Penelope Trunk</a> wrote an upbeat article=
 in <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Boston_Globe" title=3D"=
The Boston Globe">The Boston Globe</a></i> in 2006, entitled "Blogs 'essent=
ial' to a good career".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-77" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-77"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>77<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> She was on=
e of the first journalists to point out that a large portion of bloggers ar=
e professionals and that a well-written blog can help attract employers.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Business_owners">Business o=
wners</h4></div>
<p>Business owners who blog about their business can also run into legal co=
nsequences. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Cuban" title=3D"M=
ark Cuban">Mark Cuban</a>, owner of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Dallas_Mavericks" title=3D"Dallas Mavericks">Dallas Mavericks</a>, wa=
s fined during the 2006 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_B=
asketball_Association" title=3D"National Basketball Association">NBA</a> pl=
ayoffs for criticizing NBA officials on the court and in his blog.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-78" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Blog#cite_note-78"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>78<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Political_dangers">Politica=
l dangers</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Political_repression_of_=
cyber-dissidents" title=3D"Political repression of cyber-dissidents">Politi=
cal repression of cyber-dissidents</a></div>
<p>Blogging can sometimes have unforeseen consequences in politically sensi=
tive areas. In some countries, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Int=
ernet_police" title=3D"Internet police">Internet police</a> or <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secret_police" title=3D"Secret police">secret =
police</a> may monitor blogs and arrest blog authors or commentators. Blogs=
 can be much harder to control than broadcast or print media because a pers=
on can create a blog whose authorship is hard to trace by using anonymity t=
echnology such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tor_(network)" t=
itle=3D"Tor (network)">Tor</a>. As a result, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Totalitarianism" title=3D"Totalitarianism">totalitarian</a> and =
authoritarian regimes often seek to suppress blogs and punish those who mai=
ntain them.
</p><p>In Singapore, two ethnic Chinese individuals were <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imprisoned" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Imprisone=
d">imprisoned</a> under the country's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Sedition_Act_(Singapore)" title=3D"Sedition Act (Singapore)">anti-sedit=
ion law</a> for posting <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Islamophob=
ia" title=3D"Islamophobia">anti-Muslim</a> remarks in their blogs.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-79" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Blog#cite_note-79"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>79<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Egyptian blogger <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Kareem_Amer" title=3D"Kareem Amer">Kareem Amer</a> was cha=
rged with insulting the Egyptian president <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Hosni_Mubarak" title=3D"Hosni Mubarak">Hosni Mubarak</a> and an <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Islam" title=3D"Islam">Islamic</a> <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Azhar_University" title=3D"Al-Az=
har University">institution</a> through his blog. It is the first time in t=
he history of Egypt that a blogger was prosecuted. After a brief trial sess=
ion that took place in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandria"=
 title=3D"Alexandria">Alexandria</a>, the blogger was found guilty and sent=
enced to prison terms of three years for insulting <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Islam" title=3D"Islam">Islam</a> and inciting sedition and=
 one year for insulting Mubarak.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-80" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-80"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>80<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Eg=
yptian blogger Abdel Monem Mahmoud was arrested in April 2007 for anti-gove=
rnment writings in his blog. Monem is a member of the then banned <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muslim_Brotherhood" title=3D"Muslim Broth=
erhood">Muslim Brotherhood</a>. After the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/2011_Egyptian_revolution" title=3D"2011 Egyptian revolution">2011 E=
gyptian revolution</a>, the Egyptian blogger <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Maikel_Nabil_Sanad" title=3D"Maikel Nabil Sanad">Maikel Nabil Sa=
nad</a> was charged with insulting the military for an article he wrote on =
his personal blog and sentenced to three years.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-81" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-81"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>81<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p><p>After expressing opinions in his personal blog about the state of th=
e Sudanese armed forces, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jan_Pronk=
" title=3D"Jan Pronk">Jan Pronk</a>, United Nations Special Representative =
for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sudan" title=3D"Sudan">Sudan</=
a>, was given three days notice to leave Sudan. The Sudanese army had deman=
ded his deportation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-82" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-82"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>82<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-83" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#=
cite_note-83"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>83<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Myanm=
ar" title=3D"Myanmar">Myanmar</a>, Nay Phone Latt, a blogger, was sentenced=
 to 20 years in jail for posting a cartoon critical of head of state <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Than_Shwe" title=3D"Than Shwe">Than Shwe=
</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-84" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-84"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>84<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Personal_safety">Personal s=
afety</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyberstalking" title=3D"=
Cyberstalking">Cyberstalking</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Internet_homicide" title=3D"Internet homicide">Internet homicide</a></di=
v>
<p>One consequence of blogging is the possibility of online or in-person at=
tacks or threats against the blogger, sometimes without apparent reason. In=
 some cases, bloggers have faced <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
yberbullying" title=3D"Cyberbullying">cyberbullying</a>. <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kathy_Sierra" title=3D"Kathy Sierra">Kathy Sierra</a=
>, author of the blog "Creating Passionate Users",<sup id=3D"cite_ref-85" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-=
85"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>85<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> was the target of threats and <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Misogynistic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Misogynistic">miso=
gynistic</a> insults to the point that she cancelled her keynote speech at =
a technology conference in San Diego, fearing for her safety.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-86" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog=
#cite_note-86"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>86<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> While a blogger's anonymity is often tenuous, <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troll_(Internet)" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Troll (Internet)">Internet trolls</a> who would attack a blogg=
er with threats or insults can be emboldened by the anonymity of the online=
 environment, where some users are known only by a pseudonymous "username" =
(e.g., "Hacker1984"). Sierra and supporters initiated an online discussion =
aimed at countering abusive online behaviour<sup id=3D"cite_ref-87" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog#cite_note-87">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>87<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> and developed a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blogge=
r%27s_Code_of_Conduct" title=3D"Blogger's Code of Conduct">Blogger's Code o=
f Conduct</a>, which set out a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cod=
e_of_conduct" title=3D"Code of conduct">rules for behaviour</a> in the onli=
ne space.
</p>
